{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c86cad04-9a15-4e74-b4d0-7dadf07bb47a","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but here's the general guidance for recovering a crash dump on macOS for a NativeAOT app without `createdump`:\n\n## Steps to recover a macOS crash dump (NativeAOT, no createdump)\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n   mkdir -p /tmp/cores\n   ```\n\n2. **Check for Apple crash reports:**  \n   Look in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for `.ips` / `.crash` files generated automatically by ReportCrash.\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** with core dumps enabled. The core file lands at the path configured by `kern.corefile`.\n\n4. **If core dumps are still not appearing**, ensure SIP isn't blocking them and that the binary isn't code-signed with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement missing. Re-sign with:\n   ```bash\n   codesign -s - --entitlements entitlements.plist ./yourapp\n   ```\n   where `entitlements.plist` includes `com.apple.security.get-task-allow = true`.\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/cores/core.12345 ./yourapp\n   ```\n\nSince NativeAOT doesn't bundle `createdump`, you rely entirely on the OS-level core dump mechanism (`/cores/`) and Apple's built-in crash reporter.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5fa15d77-fbe0-4fe6-a1d5-b0ace30b67f7","outputTokens":393,"requestId":"5020:B7F6F:288CB4:32921B:69F55536"},"id":"c24b4232-6823-4129-b69c-efe66fac4ecc","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:37:03.715Z","parentId":"828fc261-df74-4c74-8fc3-6a213cbe21cc"}
